        <h3 class="article__heading">Challenge</h3>

        <p>Consulting is hard. Having difficult conversations with clients (oftentimes on the fly) is extra hard. This pain point became a common theme brought up in my one-on-ones with designers, as well as in our monthly office chats. Developers and designers alike found consulting increasingly more difficult as their challenges became more and more complicated. Startup co-founders required a different consulting toolkit than the head of an innovation team in an enterprise. And more client developers, designers, and project managers added to a team meant more precise, deliberate, and transparent communication.</p>

        <p>These challenges sparked some questions: How do we level-up our team on consulting skills? How do we give our team the safe space needed to try out different responses and approaches to difficult conversations?</p>

        <h3 class="article__heading">Solution</h3>

        <p>I developed a Difficult Conversations roleplaying workshop that I ran with our entire team in Boston. I chose roleplaying because I find it‚Äôs the most effective way to practice these scenarios in a safe space, while still getting input, insight, and support from other team members. I wrote up a bunch of common scenarios, and had the team split up into small groups and role play two sides of the story: the client‚Äôs perspective and thoughtbot‚Äôs perspective. I thought it was equally important that they also put themselves in the client‚Äôs shoes, to build empathy and rethink the situation through their eyes and motivations.</p>

